revision.text:
'''Archaeomythology''' refers to the study of [[archaeology]] through the discipline of [[mythology]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Haarmann|first=Harald |title=Introducing the mythological crescent: ancient beliefs and imagery connecting Eurasia with Anatolia|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|date=2008|page=7|isbn=978-3-447-05832-2}}</ref> It is an approach developed by [[Marija Gimbutas]] and mainly applied to Eastern European countries. Commenting in The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology of Ritual and Religion, Tõnno Jonuks wrote "Despite stressing the importance of archaeology and using its sources to a greater extent than any other school in the Baltic countries, studies of archaeo-mythology are still based upon folklore and archaeology has only been used selectively. The greater part of archaeological material which could not be reconciled with folklore has been left out and many phenomena of past religions have thus not been discussed as they cannot be compared with folklore."<ref name=Jonuks>{{cite book|last1=Jonuks|first1=Tõnno|title=The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology of Ritual and Religion|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0199232444|page=882|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SgLxGuvnezUC&pg=PA882&dq=Archaeomythology&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBjgKahUKEwjctteLxuLIAhUGthoKHcnkAic#v=onepage&q=Archaeomythology&f=false|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref>
