{{About|an Angolan demon||Kishi (disambiguation){{!}}Kishi}}
The '''kishi''' is a two-faced [[demon]] in [[Angola]]. According to legend, a kishi has an attractive [[human]] man's face on the front of its body and a [[hyena]]'s face on the back. Kishi are said to use their human face, as well as smooth talk and other charms to attract young women, who they then eat with the hyena face.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mack |first=Carol K. |author2=Dinah Mack  |year=1999 |title=A Field Guide to Demons, Fairies, Fallen Angels, and Other Subversive Spirits |publisher=Macmillan http://www.newstatesman.com/books/2008/12/carol-mack-demons-fairies}}</ref> The hyena face is said to have long sharp teeth and jaws so strong they cannot be pulled off anything it bites.

The word ''kishi'', ''nkishi'', or ''mukisi'' means "spirit" in several [[Bantu languages]] spoken in [[Zaire]], northern [[Zambia]], and [[Angola]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Knappert |first=Jan |year=1977 |title=Bantu Myths and Other Tales |publisher=Brill Archive}}</ref>

