{{biblio|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox art movement | name = Lowbrow | image = | alt = Image of Ryden's 2007 painting, "The Tree of Life" | caption = ''The Tree of Life'' (2007) by [[Mark Ryden]] | yearsactive = 1979–present | country = United States | majorfigures = [[Robert Williams (artist)|Williams]], [[Mark Ryden|Ryden]] | influences = [[Pop art]], [[surrealism]] | influenced = [[Designer toy]]s }} '''Lowbrow''', or '''lowbrow art''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthistory.about.com/od/arthistory101/a/lowbrow.htm|title=The Lowbrow Movement - Art History 101 Basics|publisher=}}</ref> describes an underground [[visual art]] movement that arose in the [[Los Angeles, California]], area in the late 1970s. It is a populist art movement with its cultural roots in [[underground comix]], [[punk music]], [[tiki culture]], and [[hot-rod]] cultures of the street. It is also often known by the name '''pop surrealism'''. Lowbrow art often has a sense of humor &ndash; sometimes the humor is gleeful, sometimes impish, and sometimes it is a sarcastic comment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthistory.about.com/od/arthistory101/a/lowbrow.htm|title=The Lowbrow Movement - Art History 101 Basics|publisher=}}</ref>
Most lowbrow artworks are [[painting]]s, but there are also [[Designer toys|toy]]s, [[digital art]], and [[sculpture]].
==History== Some of the first artists to create what came to be known as lowbrow art were underground cartoonists like [[Robert Williams (artist)|Robert Williams]] and [[Gary Panter]]. Early shows were in alternative [[art gallery|galleries]] in New York and Los Angeles such as Psychedelic Solutions Gallery in Greenwich Village, New York City which was run by Jacaeber Kastor, [[La Luz de Jesus]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laluzdejesus.com/|title=La Luz De Jesus - The birthplace of pop surrealismLa Luz De Jesus - The birthplace of pop surrealism|website=La Luz De Jesus}}</ref> run by Billy Shire<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billyshirefinearts.com/|title=Billy Shire Fine Arts|website=www.billyshirefinearts.com}}</ref> and [[01 gallery]] in Hollywood, run by John Pochna. The movement steadily grew from its beginning, with hundreds of artists adopting this style. As the number of artists grew, so did the number of galleries showing Lowbrow; The arbiter Greg Escalante helped produce the first formal art gallery exhibition to take low brow art seriously at the [http://www.juliericogallery.com Julie Rico Gallery] in Santa Monica with the one-man show "Looney Virtues", in 1992 by artist [http://ausgangart.com Anthony Ausgang.] The Bess Cutler Gallery also went on to show important artists and helped expand the kind of art that was classified as Lowbrow. The lowbrow magazine ''[[Juxtapoz]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juxtapoz.com|title=Juxtapoz Magazine - Home|website=www.juxtapoz.com}}</ref> by Robert Williams, first published in 1994, has been a mainstay of writing on lowbrow art and has helped direct and grow the movement.
Writers have noted that there are now distinctions to be drawn between how lowbrow manifests itself in different regions and places. Some see a distinct U.S. "west coast" lowbrow style, which is more heavily influenced by tiki, underground comix and hot rod car-culture than elsewhere. As the lowbrow style has spread around the world, it has been intermingled with the tendencies in the visual arts of those places in which it has established itself. As lowbrow develops, there may be a branching (as there was with previous art movements) into different strands and even whole new art movements. {{Citation needed|date=June 2007}}
==Origin of the term "lowbrow art"== In an article in the February 2006 issue of his magazine ''Juxtapoz'', Robert Williams took credit for originating the term "lowbrow art." He stated that in 1979 [[Gilbert Shelton]] of the publisher [[Rip Off Press]] decided to produce a book featuring Willams' paintings. Williams said he decided to give the book the self-deprecating title ''The Lowbrow Art of Robt. Williams'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beinart.org/info/essays/robert-williams.php|title=beinArt Gallery - A curated space for highly skilled figurative artists with a shared fascination for strange & imaginative themes|website=beinArt Gallery|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509085309/http://beinart.org/info/essays/robert-williams.php|archivedate=2008-05-09|df=}}</ref> since no authorized art institution would recognize his type of art. "Lowbrow" was thus used by Williams in opposition to "[[highbrow]]." He said the name then stuck, even though he feels it is inappropriate. Williams refers to the movement as "cartoon-tainted abstract surrealism<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beinart.org/info/essays/robert-williams.php|title=beinArt Gallery - A curated space for highly skilled figurative artists with a shared fascination for strange & imaginative themes|website=beinArt Gallery|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509085309/http://beinart.org/info/essays/robert-williams.php|archivedate=2008-05-09|df=}}</ref> ." Lately, Williams has begun referring to his own work as "Conceptual Realism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9WxJ44T2tX0&feature=related|title=Robert Williams on Art News 02|first=|last=sketchv|date=14 February 2010|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>"
==Books== There are several books which offer overview histories of lowbrow, including the following: * Billy Shire. (2011 ''La Luz de Jesus 25''. {{ISBN|978-0-86719-764-8}}. A collection of La Luz de Jesus Gallery in Hollywood, CA that has carried Lowbrow art for 25 years. * Kirsten Anderson. (2005) ''Pop Surrealism: The Rise of Underground Art''. {{ISBN|0-86719-618-1}} * Matt Dukes Jordan. (2005) ''Weirdo Deluxe: The Wild World of Pop Surrealism and Lowbrow Art''. San Francisco: Chronicle Books. {{ISBN|0-8118-4241-X}} * Aaron Rose and Christian Strike. (2004). ''Beautiful Losers: Contemporary Art and Street Culture''. {{ISBN|1-891024-74-4}} * Sherri Cullison. (2002) ''Vicious, Delicious, and Ambitious: 20th Century Women Artists''. {{ISBN|0-7643-1634-6}}
